In 2006, she claimed that she was verbally abused and denied entry into Udit Narayan Jha’s residence in Mumbai. Later, she received the same treatment when she visited her in-laws’ house in Nepal. “Since then, I’ve been compelled to live at my parental home in Supaul,” she alleged in her complaint to the Supaul police.

She further said that she had also filed cases in the Family Court in Supaul and approached the Women’s Commission. Udit Narayan Jha, she claimed, has “accepted” her as his wife in writing during proceedings and has also submitted a compromise petition. “But I have received neither respect nor any kind of support from my husband, Udit Narayan Jha or his family since then. I want justice,” she alleged.

